\par Casting a }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 spell has two effects. First, it creates an interdimensional connection between your plane of existence and a plane you specify, allowing travel between those two planes in either direction.
\par Second, you may then call a particular individual or kind of being through the }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate.
\par }{\fs20\cf0 The }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 itself is a circular hoop or disk from 5 to 20 feet in diameter (caster\rquote s choice), oriented in the direction you desire when it comes into existence (typically vertical and
 facing you). It is a two-dimensional window looking into the plane you specified when casting the spell, and anyone or anything that moves through is shunted instantly to the other side.
\par A }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 has a front and a back. Creatures moving through the }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 from the front are transported to the other plane; creatures moving through it from the back are not.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Planar Travel: }{\fs20\cf0 As a mode of planar travel, a }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 spell functions much like a }{\i\fs20\cf0 plane shift }{\fs20\cf0 spell, except that the }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 
opens precisely at the point you desire (a creation effect). Deities and other beings who rule a planar realm can prevent a }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 
from opening in their presence or personal demesnes if they so desire. Travelers need not join hands with you\emdash anyone who chooses to step through the portal is transported. A }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 
cannot be opened to another point on the same plane; the spell works only for interplanar travel.
\par You may hold the }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 open only for a brief time (no more than 1 round per caster level), and you must concentrate on doing so, or else the interplanar connection is severed.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Calling Creatures: }{\fs20\cf0 The second effect of the }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 
spell is to call an extraplanar creature to your aid (a calling effect). By naming a particular being or kind of being as you cast the spell, you cause the }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 to open in th
e immediate vicinity of the desired creature and pull the subject through, willing or unwilling. Deities and unique beings are under no compulsion to come through the }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate, }{\fs20\cf0 
although they may choose to do so of their own accord. This use of the spell creates a }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 that remains open just long enough to transport the called creatures. This use of the spell has an XP cost (see below).
\par If you choose to call a kind of creature instead of a known individual you may call either a single creature (of any HD) or sev
eral creatures. You can call and control several creatures as long as their HD total does not exceed your caster level. In the case of a single creature, you can control it if its HD do not exceed twice your caster level. A single creature with more HD th
an twice your caster level can\rquote 
t be controlled. Deities and unique beings cannot be controlled in any event. An uncontrolled being acts as it pleases, making the calling of such creatures rather dangerous. An uncontrolled being may return to its home plane at any time.
\par A controlled creature can be commanded to perform a service for you. Such services fall into two categories: immediate tasks and contractual service. Fighting for you in a single battle or taking any other actions that can be accomplished with
in 1 round per caster level counts as an immediate task; you need not make any agreement or pay any reward for the creature\rquote s help. The creature departs at the end of the spell.
\par If you choose to exact a longer or more involved form of service from a called creature, you must offer some fair trade in return for that service. The service exacted must be reasonable with respect to the promised favor or reward; see the }{\i\fs20\cf0 
lesser planar ally }{\fs20\cf0 spell for appropriate rewards. (Some creatures may want their payment in \'93livestock\'94
 rather than in coin, which could involve complications.) Immediately upon completion of the service, the being is transported to your vicinity, and you must then and there turn over the promised reward. After this is done, the creature is instan
tly freed to return to its own plane.
\par Failure to fulfill the promise to the letter results in your being subjected to service by the creature or by its liege and master, at the very least. At worst, the creature or its kin may attack you.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Note: }{\fs20\cf0 When you use a calling spell such as }{\i\fs20\cf0 gate }{\fs20\cf0 to call an air, chaotic, earth, evil, fire, good, lawful, or water creature, it becomes a spell of that type.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 XP Cost: }{\fs20\cf0 1,000 XP (only for the }{\i\fs20\cf0 calling creatures }{\fs20\cf0 function).
