\par This powerful inscription harms those who enter, pass, or open the warded area or object. A }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph of warding }{\fs20\cf0 can guard a bridge or passage, ward a portal, trap a chest or box, and so on.
\par You set the conditions of the ward. Typically, any creature entering the warded area or opening the warded object without speaking a password (which you set when casting the spell) is subject to the magic it stores. Alternatively or in addition to a pas
sword trigger, }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyphs }{\fs20\cf0 can be set according to physical characteristics (such as height or weight) or creature type, subtype, or kind. }{\i\fs20\cf0 Glyphs }{\fs20\cf0 
can also be set with respect to good, evil, law, or chaos, or to pass those of your religion. They cannot be set according to class, Hit Dice, or level. }{\i\fs20\cf0 Glyphs }{\fs20\cf0 
respond to invisible creatures normally but are not triggered by those who travel past them ethereally. Multiple }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyphs }{\fs20\cf0 cannot be cast on the same area. However, if a cabinet has three drawers, each can be separately warded.

\par When casting the spell, you weave a tracery of faintly glowing lines around the warding sigil. A }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph }{\fs20\cf0 can be placed to conform to any shape up to the limitations of your total square footage. When the spell is completed, the }{
\i\fs20\cf0 glyph }{\fs20\cf0 and tracery become nearly invisible.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Glyphs }{\fs20\cf0 cannot be affected or bypassed by such means as physical or magical probing, though they can be dispelled. }{\i\fs20\cf0 Mislead}{\fs20\cf0 , }{\i\fs20\cf0 polymorph}{\fs20\cf0 , and }{\i\fs20\cf0 nondetection }{\fs20\cf0 
(and similar magical effects) can fool a }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph}{\fs20\cf0 , though nonmagical disguises and the like can\rquote t. }{\i\fs20\cf0 Read magic }{\fs20\cf0 allows you to identify a }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph of warding }{\fs20\cf0 
with a DC 13 Spellcraft check. Identifying the }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph }{\fs20\cf0 does not discharge it and allows you to know the basic nature of the }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph }{\fs20\cf0 (version, type of damage caused, what spell is stored).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Note: }{\fs20\cf0 Magic traps such as }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph of warding }{\fs20\cf0 are hard to detect and disable. A rogue (only) can use the Search skill to find the }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph }{\fs20\cf0 and Disable Device to thwart it. 
The DC in each case is 25 + spell level, or 28 for }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph of warding}{\fs20\cf0 .
\par Depending on the version selected, a }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph }{\fs20\cf0 either blasts the intruder or activates a spell.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Blast Glyph: }{\fs20\cf0 A }{\i\fs20\cf0 blast glyph }{\fs20\cf0 deals 1d8 points of damage per two caster levels (maximum 5d8) to th
e intruder and to all within 5 feet of him or her. This damage is acid, cold, fire, electricity, or sonic (caster\rquote 
s choice, made at time of casting). Each creature affected can attempt a Reflex save to take half damage. Spell resistance applies against this effect.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Spell Glyph: }{\fs20\cf0 You can store any harmful spell of 3rd level or lower that you know. All level-dependent features of the spell are based on your caster level at the time of casting the }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph. }{\fs20\cf0 
If the spell has a target, it targets the intruder. If th
e spell has an area or an amorphous effect the area or effect is centered on the intruder. If the spell summons creatures, they appear as close as possible to the intruder and attack. Saving throws and spell resistance operate as normal, except that the D
C is based on the level of the spell stored in the }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph}{\fs20\cf0 .
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Material Component: }{\fs20\cf0 You trace the }{\i\fs20\cf0 glyph }{\fs20\cf0 with incense, which must first be sprinkled with powdered diamond worth at least 200 gp.
